                Title = "Strange Case of Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde: The Double Life of Respectability and Repression",
                Introduction = "A chilling tale of duality and self-destruction, Strange Case of Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde explores what happens when a man tries to separate his darker impulses from the polite mask he shows the world.",
                Content =
                    """
                Robert Louis Stevenson’s Strange Case of Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde is a compact but powerful exploration of human duality, secrecy, and the danger of denying our darker impulses. Set in Victorian London—a city of fog, narrow streets, and strict social codes—the novella follows the respectable Dr. Henry Jekyll, a well-known and charitable physician, and his sinister associate, Mr. Edward Hyde. Through the eyes of Mr. Utterson, a lawyer and Jekyll’s friend, the story gradually uncovers the horrifying truth: Jekyll and Hyde are the same person, two sides of one soul, divided by a dangerous scientific experiment.

                The narrative begins with a sense of unease rather than immediate horror. Utterson hears a disturbing story about a mysterious man, Hyde, who tramples a young girl in the street and callously tries to walk away. The situation is only resolved when Hyde is forced to pay compensation, using a cheque signed by Dr. Jekyll. This strange connection between a respected gentleman and an obviously cruel figure immediately suggests something rotten beneath the surface of respectability. Utterson, a methodical and cautious man, is unsettled by the possibility that his old friend is being blackmailed—or involved in something shameful that cannot be openly named.

                Stevenson situates the drama in a society obsessed with outward appearance. In Victorian London, reputation is everything: gentlemen guard their good names as fiercely as they guard their property. Public morality is rigid, but private desires and temptations still exist. The gulf between what people feel and what they are allowed to show creates a pressure cooker of repression. Dr. Jekyll, a man of good standing and generous acts, cannot reconcile his inner urges with the expectations placed on him. Rather than acknowledge and integrate his darker, more selfish impulses, he decides to separate them completely, creating a physical and moral divide between “good” and “evil.”

                Jekyll’s scientific experiment, which produces the figure of Hyde, is his attempt to solve this internal conflict. By concocting a potion that transforms him, Jekyll believes he can live a double life: upright doctor by day, anonymous pleasure-seeker by night. Hyde, smaller and younger-seeming than Jekyll, embodies the unrestrained, immoral side of his personality. He is free from guilt, shame, and social responsibility. Under the cover of Hyde’s identity, Jekyll can indulge impulses he dare not own in his respectable persona. At first, this feels like liberation—a way to have the best of both worlds without consequence.

                But the experiment reveals a deeper truth: Hyde is not an equal half; he is stronger, more concentrated, more potent. By splitting his nature, Jekyll gives his darker self an independent form, unsoftened by conscience or habit. Hyde grows increasingly cruel and violent, moving from callous harm to deliberate murder. The infamous killing of Sir Danvers Carew, a kind and harmless man, shows how far Hyde has gone. The attack is savage and senseless, suggesting that once freed from the restraints of Jekyll’s moral sense, Hyde’s capacity for evil is not limited by any rational motive.

                The transformation between Jekyll and Hyde becomes less voluntary as time passes. Initially, Jekyll chooses when to drink the potion and change form. However, the power dynamic shifts: Hyde starts appearing without the potion, intruding into Jekyll’s life at unexpected, terrifying moments. The boundary Jekyll believed he could control begins to erode. He wakes up in Hyde’s body, trapped, and must scramble to reverse the change. This loss of control underscores one of the story’s central warnings: you cannot completely isolate and “safely” indulge your worst impulses without risking that they will eventually dominate you.

                The physical descriptions of Jekyll and Hyde emphasize this moral imbalance. Hyde is repeatedly described as deformed, though no one can clearly say how. People feel an instinctive loathing when they see him, as if their bodies recognize something wrong: an absence of empathy, a raw selfishness made flesh. Jekyll, in contrast, is tall, well-formed, and dignified, with a face that expresses kindness. The contrast suggests that outward form reflects inner character—yet Stevenson also complicates this idea. Jekyll and Hyde share the same soul, and the horror lies not in a monster invading from outside, but in what emerges from within when constraints are removed.

                Mr. Utterson’s role as narrator adds to the sense of mystery and repression. A lawyer and man of principle, Utterson approaches the case with rational caution. He does not leap to supernatural conclusions; instead, he suspects blackmail, madness, or scandal. His investigation is piecemeal, based on wills, letters, and witness accounts. The reader uncovers the truth alongside him, moving from suspicion to horror as the clues accumulate. The narrative structure—with letters and confessions tucked into the story—mirrors the theme of secrets hidden behind respectable fronts. Only at the very end, when Jekyll’s full confession is read, does the whole picture come into view.

                The setting of London—foggy, dark, full of twisted alleys and closed doors—enhances the atmosphere of duality. Streets appear respectable by day and sinister by night. Houses have cheerful front entrances and hidden back doors, just as people have public and private selves. Jekyll’s own home symbolizes this split: the pleasant, well-kept front where he receives guests, and the dingy laboratory at the back where Hyde comes and goes. The city itself feels like a physical map of Jekyll’s divided mind, with its clear thoroughfares, shadowy passages, and areas no one wants to examine too closely.

                Thematically, Strange Case of Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde engages with Victorian anxieties about morality, science, and the nature of the self. Jekyll’s experiment represents both the promise and the danger of scientific progress. By meddling with the human psyche, he disrupts the balance that allows him to function. Stevenson raises a question that still feels modern: if we could strip away conscience and societal constraints, what would remain? Jekyll believes he can neatly separate “good” and “evil,” but the experiment reveals that identity is not so easily partitioned. The darker side, once empowered, does not stay politely in its own box.

                The novella can also be read as a critique of repressive social norms. Jekyll’s problem is not that he has dark impulses—everyone does—but that he believes he must either hide them completely or give them total control in the form of Hyde. There is no middle space in his mind for honest acknowledgment and integration. Victorian society’s insistence on purity and outward perfection leaves no room for people to admit imperfection without shame. In this reading, Hyde is not just Jekyll’s evil twin; he is the product of a culture that forces its members to bury any unacceptable parts of themselves until those parts emerge in distorted, uncontrollable forms.

                Jekyll’s confession at the end provides the story’s emotional and philosophical climax. He explains how he came to view his nature as “profoundly a double,” how he crafted the potion, and how intoxicating it felt to become Hyde. He admits that Hyde allowed him to do things he would not have done as Jekyll—not because the desires were new, but because the guilt was removed. Yet he also recognizes too late that he underestimated Hyde’s hold. The confession is full of regret and terror, as Jekyll watches his own personality shrinking while Hyde grows stronger. The final lines, in which Jekyll feels Hyde closing in permanently, are both a confession of guilt and a record of an inner self being overrun.

                The ending—Jekyll’s death, with Hyde’s body left behind—is ambiguous in moral tone. On one hand, the immediate threat of Hyde is gone; the murders and brutality will stop. On the other, the story does not suggest that the potential for such duality has vanished from humanity at large. It feels more like a case study, a warning. Jekyll’s attempt to neatly divide his moral self has failed catastrophically, but the underlying tension between public virtue and private desire remains. The horror lingers in the implication that the capacity for both Jekyll and Hyde exists in everyone, and that the line between them may be thinner than we would like to believe.

                Strange Case of Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde is short, but its influence has been enormous. Its core idea—the double life, the hidden self that emerges when no one is watching—has become a cultural shorthand for hypocrisy, repression, and inner conflict. The phrase “Jekyll and Hyde” is used to describe people who seem to switch personalities, but Stevenson’s story is more subtle than that cliché. It isn’t simply about a “good” side and a “bad” side; it’s about what happens when a person refuses to accept the complexity of their own nature and instead tries to split themselves into incompatible halves.

                Ultimately, the novella invites readers to consider their own masks and shadows. Rather than offering a simple moral rule, Stevenson poses a more unsettling question: what parts of ourselves do we deny, and what danger lies in pretending that our darker impulses are not ours at all? In the foggy streets of Jekyll’s London and the locked rooms of his house, we see a reflection of a deeper human truth—that each person contains conflicting drives, and that how we acknowledge and manage them may determine whether we live as integrated beings or slowly become strangers to ourselves.
